result.execSummary:
The defendant Dashanti G Bennett was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Vehicle Operator Flee/Elude Officer, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Dashanti G Bennett in court with attorney Lisa M. Procaccio.  Defendant Dashanti G Bennett in custody.  Timothy J. Cotter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

  Sentencing proceeds.  Statements made by the state, defense counsel and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:  Defendant sentenced to serve 120 DAYS at the HOUSE OF CORRECTION, consecutive to any other sentence. 
Credit for ZERO days time served. 

COURT STAYS sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for a period of 18 MONTHS under the supervision of the Wisconsin Department of Corrections.
.
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION (AS TO COUNT 1): 
* Comply with the standard rules of probation.
* Complete a job training program to enhance ability to obtain employment.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* Provide a DNA sample (unless previously done) and PAY DNA surcharge - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* No driving without a valid driver's license.

  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Appeal rights given.

Defendant Dashanti G Bennett in court with attorney Lisa M. Procaccio.  Defendant Dashanti G Bennett in custody.  Timothy J. Cotter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to her plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised she is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised she is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
